<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/3EAE04CA-9D62-4483-B9C4-F91AD9F4C5A9"><gtr:id>3EAE04CA-9D62-4483-B9C4-F91AD9F4C5A9</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Oxford</gtr:name><gtr:department>Environmental Change Institute SoGE</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>University Chest</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>Wellington Square</gtr:line2><gtr:line4>Oxford</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>OX1 2JD</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>South East</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/3EAE04CA-9D62-4483-B9C4-F91AD9F4C5A9"><gtr:id>3EAE04CA-9D62-4483-B9C4-F91AD9F4C5A9</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Oxford</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>University Chest</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>Wellington Square</gtr:line2><gtr:line4>Oxford</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>OX1 2JD</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>South East</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/8E0B92BC-3157-4812-AE3C-987F840A5510"><gtr:id>8E0B92BC-3157-4812-AE3C-987F840A5510</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Kamal</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Kapadia</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FH024158%2F1"><gtr:id>F2EFAE34-E89F-4A5D-A081-E291C37DAB2E</gtr:id><gtr:title>Developments after a Disaster: The Tsunami, Poverty, Conflict and Reconstruction in Sri Lanka</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/H024158/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This research analysed the aid response in Sri Lanka to the tsunami disaster of December 2004, seeking to understand why the longer-term recovery effort performed poorly. It examined:&lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>&amp;nbsp;livelihoods recovery efforts;&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>a program to foster participation in housing reconstruction projects; &lt;/li>

 &lt;li>efforts to use tsunami aid to institute a peace agreement between the Sri Lankan government and the LTTE, a rebel group.&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>

&lt;p>Drawing guidance from the political ecology literature on disasters and development, it studied how power dynamics between various groups affected these programs. Ethnographic and survey methods helped reveal that aid programs were founded on certain poorly conceived ideas (in key aid agencies) about the nature of the Sri Lankan economy and politics, resulting in poor design. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The study concluded that in a disaster, the stakes of power relations are greatly enhanced, but the way power manifests is shaped fundamentally by the historically-specific context. Ignoring these power relations and their context was a key reason why aid programs failed to achieve their goals. It also concluded that theory must be built up from a deep engagement with the places one is trying to rebuild, and recommendations were provided for how this can be achieved. &lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2012-05-10</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2010-05-11</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>84104</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">ES/H024158/1</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>B57EEFB7-602E-4F5D-92E4-A0C265266249</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Demography &amp; human geography</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>EBACD6D4-D1E5-4970-8BEC-7F4568EB26BA</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Development studies</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>E844174D-6A1C-4D2D-8F24-57698F7DA353</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Environmental planning</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject><gtr:rese